	</div><div>

	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		Continuing our discussion from <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/008419.asp">Part I</a> of this Q/A session, I answer yet more reader questions!<br><hr><br/><b>Hill</b> asks: <i>This may have been answered earlier in your blogs, but I only started reading a few months ago. How do you get into this business? What experiance[sic], training do you have? How did you get started consulting, did you work under a mentor first, like Scrap? I'm all ears. And thanks for such an entertaining read.</i><br/><br/>Answer: This is the #1 question I am asked in the blog and in e-mail.   My adventure in this type of business started just before the internet boom of the mid 90's.  I had always been interested in computers, and have my father to thank for buying me my first personal computer: a Commodore Vic-20!  I checked out every book on computer programming from the local library and got to work.  Later in life, I continued my passion for computers and electronics through various learning experiences - and had my first run in with 'unauthorized use of an electronic system'.  That's the nice way of saying that I got busted for gaining entry into a certain organization's VAX system through a modem and a username/password that they were nice enough to DISPLAY ON THE SCREEN AT LOGIN.  Nope, I'm not making that up.  Remember - this is a long time ago before computer security was the topic on everyone's lips.<br/><br/>Fast forward a few years through college, and I'm smack dab in the middle of desert shield/storm as a member of the US Military.  Most of my work was in signal intelligence, but I was constantly being pulled away to set up IBM personal computers and 'network the SOB's together!' as my first seargent liked to say.  It was at this point that I realized how serious computer security was - and, how to investigate unauthorized usage.  This knowledge paid off in spades, as I was able to use my knowledge in other realms within the US military / federal service.<br/><br/>Moving the time wheel forward, I'm out of the military and employed with several internet startup companies.  Most startups didn't have security as a line item in their business requirements (or their business plan for that matter).  I spent a great deal of time redesigning networks with security in mind, and associating with knowledgeable folks on the internet.  I went to every technical certification course I could, and later every security certification course I could afford.  During the late 1990's, these types of certifications paid off nicely.  <br/><br/>Consulting is a funny business.  I started off doing consulting as a side project, and it eventually took over my life at some point - and strictly on a referral basis.  However, constant travel and a heavy workload eventually took it's toll on my business and personal life.  It was at this point that I decided to hand the majority of the consulting business off to associates (like Scrap) and concentrate my work on a single (albeit large) employer.  <br/><br/>I had so many mentors through my journey that I couldn't possibly begin to name them all.  I did have one cowboy though who taught me the most important lesson of them all: put your life first, your work second.   I encourage you all to read that last part again until it sinks in.  =)<br/><br/>I'm sure there will be more details in some sort of a published work eventually ...<br/><br/><br><hr><br/><b>Michael Boman</b> asks <i>Have you ever thought about having your casefiles produced as hardcopies? I sure wouldn't mind buying a hardcopy of the best casefiles over a year (for the right price), especially if they were edited to a "Hackers Challenge" kind of format. lulu.com offers on-demand printing so it would not require you to fork up any money up front.</i><br/><br/>Answer:  Are you kidding?  I've been working on it for what seems like an eternity.  Luckily, most of the work that goes into these case files is 'timeless' so to speak.  It's not like I'm writing a book on Office 2003 or anything.  =)   The book is a spare time project (remember that whole life before work thing?) and to put all your minds at ease - it's about 85% done at my last estimation.   Publishing, well - that's a whole other topic.  Thanks for the tip on lulu.com.<br/><br/><br><hr><br/><b>CBK</b> asks <i>When you're building a casefile do you start with a goal in mind (exposing wireless security) and pull pieces together or do you start with a case and pull bits and pieces in to flesh it out and add things?</i><br/><br/>Answer: Excellent question from a very loyal reader (yo!).  As I'm sure every monkey knows, my writing is very monkey-formula.  I start with pieces of cases scattered everywhere in front of me, and I try to piece things together to do two very important things: (1) Educate the reader and (2) Entertain the reader.  Let me tell you, #2 is much harder than #1.   I do have a goal that I write towards, and sometimes I actually write backwards (as another reader pointed out to me in e-mail recently).   75% of the work that goes into these case files is continuity checking - making sure that I drop clues at the right parts, and wrap them up at the end.   I've had several readers ask "Why do you put the surprise stuff in the end like that?  How can we solve the case w/o all the data being present?!?".  Well, I'll be honest.  I don't expect you to - however, it doesn't stop readers like <b>TuxGirl</b> from doing it on a regular basis.  Part of the monkey-formula is pulled right out of the Scooby-Doo cartoon (no, I'm not making that up).  One of the things that I loved about Scooby-Doo as a child was that there was always this killer revelation at the end that you couldn't have possibly picked up through the story.  I'm quite sure that the writers did this to make Fred &amp; the gang seem that much smarter.  This is not my purpose.  I'm just a monkey - I do it for the sheer hope that when the surprise happens, the *method* being described will stick in your brain, and you'll pull it out down the road on your own case.<br/><br/><br><hr><br/><b>Donathan</b> writes <i>I want to know of a case what went bad for you and/or Scrap. One that you couldn't solve, one that your findings/techniques were questioned, maybe the perp of the case went after you personally when you caught them. Basically, when all went down the toilet, how did/do you handle it?</i><br/><br/>Answer: Ho, boy.  We have had some doozies.  I have to save some of these for the book, but I'll share a quick summary of one.  Scrap and I were tasked with investigating a bookkeeper who was 'cooking the books' at a consulting firm.  The partners *knew* she was doing it, but they couldn't *prove* it with hardcore evidence.  There were other complications: she was a minority, and played the minority card at every opportunity.  The partners knew that unless they had a smoking gun, she would retain a lawyer and quite possibly put their consulting firm out of business.   Scrap and I set up video surveillance, key-logged her workstation, and made nightly visits to the office to make forensic copies of her workstation's hard drive.  One night while we were in the middle of an imaging session (we're talking 11PM at night), she visits the office with her 300-lb gangsta-looking boyfriend.  When she saw what we were doing, we had to think quick.  We passed ourselves off as computer repair people.  She wasn't buying it.  Homeboy had a gun stuck in the front of his trousers.  (I'd like to point out that neither I nor Scrap have ever carried a weapon while consulting.)  Scrap managed to distract them with some banter while I dialed one of the partners on my cell phone and left the line 'open' praying to all hell that he'd answer and know what I was doing.  I lucked out - he figured it out and raced to the office.  The rest of the story?  Well, you'll have to keep reading the blog.  =)  I have never had my life threatened, however Scrap has - twice.  Maybe you'll all understand why he disguises his voice on the podcasts now.  <br/><br/><br><hr><br/><b>Case</b> asks a fantastic question: <i>In Leaky Leaf IX the Chief wrote about running an nslookup on the IP address found in the Limewire log:<br/><br/>    scraptop:~ scrap$ nslookup 64.xx.xx.xx<br/>    Server: 10.0.1.9<br/>    Address: 10.0.1.9#53<br/>    Name: xx-xx-xx-64.gamersbeatches.net<br/><br/><br/><br/>Chief, although we see in the end that you verified the gamersbeatches.net connection with the corroberating e-mail evididence, were you ever concerned that TreeSoft's nameserver had been altered and was fed you a red herring? Do you ever double-check lookups by using non-internal nameservers?</i><br/><br/>Answer: It is part of our standard procedure to never trust a DNS server on a local net.  Ever.  I suppose I could have mentioned this as another lesson in the story - and I'm going to add this to my lessons to add to a future case file.  In this circumstance, Scrap used a web browser and verified the DNS response with a well known lookup service.  =)<br/><br/><br><hr><br/><b>Charlene</b> asks: <i>One thing I'd like to know. I've tried to figure out what was one of the first virii in existance.<br/><br/>I helped clean up one on a CDC 6400 back around 1978.</i><br/><br/>Answer: Wow!  A CDC 6400?  I've only read about them in books.  =)  To answer your question, I would like to refer you to <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531/http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0872842.html">The Computer Virus Timeline</a> at infoplease.com.   I'm not sure I could post a better answer than what you're going to read there.  For those of you that haven't seen this - it starts in 1949!!!<br/><br><hr><br/><br/>I hope you've enjoyed this Q/A session.  Please, post more questions as comments to this blog entry - you just might get an answer!<br/><br/>Next up - The Conclusion to Lascivious Lawyer !<br/><br/>~ Chief<br/><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531/http://www.esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=27005-060329-187187-97"><img alt="esbn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/esbnicon.asp?id=2700506032918718797" border="0"> 27005-060329-187187-97</a> Rate content: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=2700506032918718797&amp;rate=yes"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbup.gif" border="0"></a><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=2700506032918718797&amp;rate=no"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbdown.gif" border="0"></a><br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/barcode.asp?code=2700506032918718797&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"></p><p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
<tr><td><img style="margin-right: 9px; float: left" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531im_/http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/s_610000.jpg"><b><font face="Arial" size="4">DID YOU KNOW?</b></font><font face="Arial" size="2"><p style="margin-top: 2px">You can read all of SecurityMonkey's case files! <br>Find them <b><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/official-securitymonkey-case-file-index-14787">here</a></b>. <br><br>You can also read all of SecurityMonkey's <br>'Banana Cupboard' stories <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131531/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/banana-cupboard-stories-index-25647">here</a>.  <br><br>You may not get a lot done for a few hours... or even days.</font><br><br>The reviews are in...<br><br><i>"Completely addictive... suspenseful and informative at the same time!"<br>"A mix of classic detective scripting, timing, and technology..."<br>"Cleverly injected humor makes these case files easy to read and hard to put down!"</i></td></tr></table><hr><p>
